Part 5: Univariate Analysis¶

We can now begin to perform Univariate Data Analysis to examine the frequencies, averages and other statistics of the individual variables. We will create definitions to help visualize the data using the next two blocks of code:

In [5]:
def histogram_boxplot(data, xlabel=None, title=None, font_scale=2, figsize=(15,7), bins=None):
    mean = np.mean(data)
    
    sns.set(font_scale=font_scale) # setting the font scale of the seaborn
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, figsize=figsize)
    sns.boxplot(data, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True,color="violet") #boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value
    sns.distplot(data,kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,palette="winter") if bins else sns.distplot(data,kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, bins=None)
    ax_hist2.axvline(mean, color='g', linestyle='--') #mean will show as vertical line in the histogram
    if xlabel: ax_hist2.set(xlabel=xlabel) #xlabel
    if title: ax_box2.set(title=title) # title of the graph
    plt.show() # for plotting the graph
In [6]:
def perc_on_bar(plot, feature):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function wont work if a colume is passed in hue parameter
    '''
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # height of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x,y), size = 20) # annotate the percentage
    plt.show() # shows the plot

Member¶

The member variable is the dependent (y) variable for logistic regression. In other words, we want to examine how the other variables affect the member variable. It is in binary format, meaning there are only two values: member (1) or casual (0). Let's plot the frequencies of the two values.

Part 6: Additional Data Processing¶

Dealing with Outliers¶

Duration¶

After the multivariate analysis, we have discovered that there are a fair number of outliers in the duration_in_s variable. This means that there are several instances where the user took the rental bike for a much longer period than is normal. Due to the scale, it is hard to discern the exact point, visually, where the outliers begin. We can apply the formula 1.5 x IQR to find the exact point. We can also use the Days data to see if we can visually find the point. Let's try that first...

In [22]:
histogram_boxplot(BD['Days'])

As we can see, anything greater than or equal to 1 day is considered an outlier. We can see from above that we have outliers ranging from 1 to 21 days, but each point may represent more than one instance. Lets do a quick count to see how many outliers there really are.

In [27]:
#calculate interquartile range of values in the 'points' column
q75, q25 = np.percentile(BD['duration_in_s'], [75 ,25])
iqr = q75 - q25

uw = 1.5 * iqr

#display the upper whisker of the boxplot, in other words, 1.5 x x IQR
uw

Now lets count how many outliers there actually are...

In [28]:
counter = 0

for index in range(0, len(BD)):
    if BD['duration_in_s'].loc[index] >= 877.5 :
        counter = counter + 1    
        

print('There are', counter, 'outliers')

There are 62409 outliers

As we can see, there are now 62,409 outliers, which becomes problematice because this represents over 25% of the entire data. We can also see that any rental over 14.63 minutes is considered an outlier by this method. At this point, we have to make a decision regarding whether we keep all outliers or whether we choose some other value. We already know that the data is not normally distributed and that there is positive skewness with a long tail to the right. The reason for choosing 1.5 for the whiskers is to get it close to the acceptable 3 standard deviations of a Guassian model, however, this assumes normal distribution. Therefore, choosing 1.5 will not help us much in this isntance. We can choose a larger number, such as 2 or even three. Or we can make a business-oriented decision, and exclude any values larger than one day. By doing this, we can focus on day-rentals. And then we have a different dataset for anything longer than 1 day, which in this case, is only 41 entries. Lets go ahead and drop anything where day >= 1 day (or duration_in_s >= 86,400)

First, we will create two copies of the dataframe BD. This allows us to have a savepoint if we need to go back. The two copies will be:

  • DR: short for Day Rides, and include all trips shorter than 86,400 seconds
  • LR: short for Long Rides and will only include trips that are equal to or longer than 86,400 seconds
In [29]:
DR = BD.copy()
In [30]:
LR = BD.copy()
In [31]:
DR.drop(DR.loc[DR['duration_in_s'] >= 86400].index, inplace=True)

We can see that nothing goes past the 86,400s limit, which is equal to one day. These outliers are considered acceptable for our purposes, since it makes sense that users may rent a bike for an entire day, in some instances.

Before we can run analysis, lets drop the variables that will not be used in the models. This is one of the reasons we made a copy of the dataset. Part 8: Building the Model¶

What are we trying to determine?¶

Recall or Precision?

  • Cyclistic can potentially face losses in one of two ways:
    • The company erroneously identifies a member as a casual rider and begins marketing to them to become a member (False Negative)
    • The company identifies a casual rider as a member and does not target them in the marketing campaign - Opportunity Loss (False Positive)

Which loss is greater ?

  • Misidentifying a member as a casual rider may be insulting or annoying to the customer. They may not feel valued at all and take their business elsewhere. Cancelling their membership is worse than not targeting a casual rider because they may not purchase a membership regardless. There is also a cost to marketing to someone who is already a member. (False Negative)

Decision

  • Recall - In this case, there is a high cost associated with a False Negative so we want to reduce the chances of a member being identified as a casual rider.
  • Recall gives the ratio of True positives to Actual positives, so high Recall implies low false negatives, i.e. low chances of predicting a member as a casual customer.

A) Logistic Regression - statsmodels¶

Approach¶

  1. Choose a Model
  2. Split the Data and Train the Model
  3. Evaluate the Model
  4. Tune the Model and Prune the Tree (if required)
  5. Check Performance

1. Choose a Model¶

For our first trial, we shall choose the statsmodel method of building a logistic regression model. This is a package in python that allows us to see the entire tree, using all the variables. This approach means that, generally, the model is overfitting the data and requires post-pruning. This can be done by checking for multicollinearity and dropping variables with insignificant p-values. The benefit of this method allows us to see all the variables within the model and how decisions are made, based on what the computer identifies as the importance of the variables. It is also a more hands-on approach, better suited to allow the user to really understand the independent variables and how they interact with the dependent variable.

2. Split the Data and Train the Model¶

In [ ]:
# Separating the dependent and independent variables into two dataframes 
X = DR.drop('member', axis=1) #Dropping the dependent variable, Loan
Y = DR['member'] # establishing Loan as the dependent variable

We must remember that, the way onehotencoding works, is that one of the dummy variables should be dropped. For instance, in the days of the week, we can drop Saturday (or any day will do, but Saturday is the last one so we will drop that). The way the computer interprets this, is that if there are zeros for the six remaining variables (Sun-Fri), then it has to be the 'other'. In other words, saturday has become irrelevant. Simiarly, we will drop docked.

3. Evaluate the Model¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report,confusion_matrix


def make_confusion_matrix(y_actual,y_predict,labels=[1, 0]):
    '''
    y_predict: prediction of class
    y_actual : ground truth  
    '''
    cm=confusion_matrix( y_predict,y_actual, labels=[1, 0])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["1","0"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['1','0']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Odds¶

  • When coefficient is b , then change in odds is (exp(b)-1)*100 %
  • Probability = odd/(1+odd)
In [ ]:
odds=((np.exp(np.abs(lg1.params)))-1)
print(odds)

Coefficient interpretations¶

  • Coefficient of Distance, and the Days of the Week are all positive, increase in these will lead to increase in chances of taking a personal loan
  • Coefficient of duration_in_s and electric are negative, increase in these will lead to decrease in chances of being a member
  • Distance: 1 unit change in Distance will change the odds of being a member by 9.11%
  • Sunday: 1 unit change will change the odds of being a member by 6.4%
  • Monday: 1 unit change will change the odds of being a member by 62.25%
  • Tuesday: 1 unit change will change the odds of being a member by 95.54%
  • Wednesday: 1 unit change will change the odds of being a member by 77.34%
  • Thursday: 1 unit change will change the odds of being a member by 57.79%

  • Friday: 1 unit change will change the odds of being a member by 30.13%

  • Distance has a small coefficients, so large changes in their value will have a smaller effect change in odds of being a member.

  • Duration_in_s has a very small negative cooeficient, meaning that it would take very big increases in duration_in_s to make it more likely the user will NOT be a member

Try to improve Recall using AUC-ROC curve

In [ ]:
# Optimal threshold as per AUC-ROC curve
# The optimal cut off would be where tpr is high and fpr is low
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, lg1.predict(X_test2))

optimal_idx = np.argmax(tpr - fpr)
optimal_threshold = thresholds[optimal_idx]
print(optimal_threshold)

Precision-Recall curve to Find a Better Threshold

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve

y_scores=lg1.predict(X_train2)
prec, rec, tre = precision_recall_curve(y_train, y_scores, )

def plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], 'b--', label='precision')
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], 'g--', label = 'recall')
    plt.xlabel('Threshold')
    plt.legend(loc='upper left')
    plt.ylim([0,1])

plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(prec, rec, tre)
plt.show()
  • At 0.70 threshold we get a higher recall and a good precision
  • Decreasing threshold beyond 0.70 will lead to fast decrease in Recall, which will lead to great loss of opportunity, so let's consider threshold of 0.70

Conclusion and Recommendations

  • The best test recall in 98.89% but the accuracy and precision is low
  • This means that the model is not good at identifying casual riders as casual riders, it makes too many mistakes believing they are members (almost 25% of all users).
  • This MAY be problematic since it drastically reduces the pool of users that Cyclistic will market to. However, this also means they will spend less on advertising and they will not have to worry about accidentally targeting a member, which is a waste of money and may alienate the customer.
  • The model performance can be improved in terms of accuracy, precision and F1 scores, but this would reduce the recall score
  • Days of the week seem to be the most important variables
